.TH SNAPDIFF 1 "2026" "snapdiff" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
snapdiff \- snapshot a directory and diff it later
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B snapdiff
.B snap
.I dir
.RB [ \-o
.IR output.snap ]
.br
.B snapdiff
.B diff
.I snapshot.snap dir
.br
.B snapdiff
.B info
.I snapshot.snap
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B snapdiff
records the state of every file in a directory tree \(em paths, sizes,
permissions, modification times, and SHA-256 content hashes \(em into a
plain-text
.I .snap
file.
Run it again later to see exactly what was added, removed, modified, or
chmod\[aq]d.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.BI snap " dir " [ \-o " file" ]
Walk
.I dir
recursively and write a snapshot to
.IR file .
If
.B \-o
is omitted the output is named after the directory basename
(e.g.\&
.I dir.snap
).
.TP
.BI diff " snapshot.snap dir"
Compare
.I dir
against a previously taken snapshot and print a summary of changes to
standard output.
.br
Exit codes mirror
.BR diff (1):
.B 0
= no differences,
.B 1
= error,
.B 2
= differences found.
.TP
.BI info " snapshot.snap"
Print metadata stored in a snapshot: root directory, creation time, file
count, and total tracked size.
.SH OUTPUT FORMAT
.SS diff output
Each changed file is prefixed with a tag:
.TP
.B [+] ADDED
File is present in the current directory but not in the snapshot.
.TP
.B [-] REMOVED
File was in the snapshot but is no longer present.
.TP
.B [~] MODIFIED
File content (SHA-256 hash) has changed. Size and hash deltas are shown.
.TP
.B [M] CHMOD
Permissions changed but content is identical.
.SS Snapshot file format
Plain text, tab-separated, designed to be
.BR grep (1)\c
- and
.BR awk (1)\c
-friendly:
.PP
.nf
# snapdiff v1
# root: /etc
# created: 1713400000
# format: path\\tsize\\tmode\\tmtime\\thash
nginx/nginx.conf	4201	644	1713399000	3f8a1b2c...
.fi
.SH EXAMPLES
Audit what an installer script touches:
.PP
.nf
snapdiff snap / \-o before.snap
./install.sh
snapdiff diff before.snap /
.fi
.PP
Track config drift in /etc:
.PP
.nf
snapdiff snap /etc \-o etc\-baseline.snap
# ... time passes ...
snapdiff diff etc\-baseline.snap /etc
.fi
.SH PERFORMANCE
File hashes are computed in parallel across all available CPU cores.
When diffing, files whose size and modification time are unchanged are
not rehashed \(em only genuinely modified files pay the SHA-256 cost.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR diff (1),
.BR sha256sum (1),
.BR find (1),
.BR stat (1)
